<HEADLINE>
FT  09 SEP 93 / Fears on resale of council houses
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IVOR OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE COMMONS environment committee has urged the government to investigate
the likely consequences for the housing market if increasing numbers of
former council properties bought by tenants cannot be re-sold, Ivor Owen
writes.
In a report published yesterday the committee highlights anecdotal evidence
that building societies are not prepared to fund mortgages when some
properties acquired by tenants under the government's 'right-to-buy' policy,
particularly high-rise flats, are placed on the market.
The cross-party committee expresses concern about the possibility of growing
numbers of 'unsaleable right-to-buy properties' and the consequent effect on
the value of surrounding homes.
Environment Committee third report 1992-93. HMSO. Pounds 18.40.
