<HEADLINE>
FT  09 SEP 93 / Watchdog backs capital standards
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NORMA COHEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE Personal Investment Authority, the proposed new self-regulatory body for
retail financial services, yesterday agreed to the controversial proposal
that anyone giving financial advice be required to have a minimum of Pounds
10,000 in capital, Norma Cohen writes.
Mr Andrew Large, chairman of the Securities and Investment Board, the chief
City watchdog, has said he will insist on minimum capital standards.
The PIA board is discussing what sort of resources may be said to constitute
capital. Minimum capital standards have been opposed.
All parts of the retail financial services industry must vote to approve the
PIA, to be formed by merging the memberships of existing regulatory
organisations, and some have threatened to boycott it if its rules are too
tough.
Mr Bill Barron, acting chief executive of PIA, said it will not
automatically accept all members of other self-regulatory organisations.
Among those who may be barred are those whose disciplinary record is poor
although not sufficiently poor to have resulted in barring them.
