<HEADLINE>
FT  09 SEP 93 / Sutherland firm on farm accord
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID BUCHAN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   PARIS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THERE CAN be no reneg-otiation of the farm trade agreement made last year
between the US and the European Community, Mr Peter Sutherland, director
general of the Gatt world trade organisation, warned Mr Edouard Balladur,
French prime minister, yesterday.
After talks between the two in Paris, Mr Sutherland said 'a significant
number' of the 108 countries negotiating in Gatt did not want the draft
agreement to be reopened, which meant 'there could not be a renegotiation'.
France, under pressure from the militant French farmers' lobby, has demanded
changes to the accord, which foresees cuts in EC agricultural export
subsidies. Both EC and Gatt officials have warned France that reopening the
deal would scupper prospects for an agreement in the Uruguay Round of Gatt
talks being reached by a December 15 deadline.
There was 'only one opportunity left' to finish the Gatt negotiations, Mr
Sutherland told the French prime minister, and that was to conclude them by
December 15. The deadline, he added, 'has been set by the negotiating
parties, not by me'.
But Mr Balladur indicated that legally the Blair House transatlantic farm
accord had never been properly concluded. He insisted - and Mr Sutherland
conceded the point in remarks after his meeting - that 'there is no European
position until the EC Council of Ministers decides'.
Mr Balladur, according to French officials, characterised the December 15
deadline as 'an American date', inserted for US political convenience. But
he went on to assure the Gatt director: 'Be sure that I want a Gatt
agreement, but I ask that all should make an effort, not just the French'.
The Blair House accord will be discussed by EC foreign ministers this
weekend and by farm and foreign ministers at a special session on September
20.
</TEXT>
