<HEADLINE>
FT  09 SEP 93 / Major and Clarke head off rightwing tax revolt: Chancellor
hints at VAT rise
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KEVIN BROWN and ROLAND ADBURGHAM
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A THREATENED revolt on tax and spending by rightwing cabinet ministers was
stopped in its tracks yesterday by a combined broadside from Mr John Major,
prime minister, and Mr Kenneth Clarke, the chancellor.
Mr Clarke also hinted strongly that an increase in the rate or scope of
value added tax was likely in the November Budget.
In an interview with the Daily Telegraph, Mr Clarke insisted that all
taxation options remained open, rejected speculation that the government
deficit might be lower than the Treasury forecast of Pounds 50bn, and ruled
out any further discussion of the cabinet's agreed public spending total of
Pounds 254bn.
Mr Major signalled his intention to end last year's Conservative drift and
disunity by launching a scathing attack on rightwing dissidents and pledging
tough long-term action to control public spending.
In an article written for evening newspapers, Mr Major gave the clearest
signal yet that spending on health and social security would be cut in the
long term.
'We need to look at the long-term difficulties in funding social expenditure
 -now outstripping inflation by some 3 per cent a year. That can't go on.'
Mr Major's tough approach to long-term spending pressures, combined with the
chancellor's uncompromising stand, cuts the ground from underneath the
rightwing cabinet minority.
The right, led by Mr Peter Lilley, social security secretary, and Mr John
Redwood, Welsh secretary, claims tax rises this year could be avoided by
more spending cuts and faster-than-expected economic growth, which would
raise government revenues.
A showdown was expected at the political cabinet - held without officials -
to follow today's cabinet, the first for six weeks. But the right may choose
to withdraw in the face of certain defeat.
The prime minister's hopes of an autumn recovery in government popularity
were boosted by an unexpectedly warm response from party activists during a
tour of the West Country.
Local officials said he blamed the Tory Eurosceptic wing for much of the
disunity which has dogged the party since the 1992 general election. 'He was
very vehement indeed on the 20 or so dissident MPs,' said one official. 'He
said this effectively reduces his majority to five.'
Mr Major's helicopter trip to the south-west was ridiculed by Mr Paddy
Ashdown, the Liberal Democrat leader, who claimed it reflected Conservative
'panic' about the party's declining support in the area.
But local Tory officials said Mr Major encountered little of the bitterness
that has emerged in the region since July, when the Liberal Democrats
overturned a Tory majority of more than 30,000 in a by-election victory.
Mr Major held private meetings with several hundred constituency chairmen
and officials at secret locations in Wiltshire, Somerset and Hampshire.
Local Tories, worried by the party's loss of support to the Liberal
Democrats over such issues as VAT on fuel and high water charges, were
enthusiastic about his performance.
Joy among Lib Dems Page 9
BR privatisation Page 20
</TEXT>
