<DOCNO>FT933-4462</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-DIHB8AHTFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>930908
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  08 SEP 93 / Survey of Software at Work - Autumn 1993 (20): Good software
tools aid Ford automation
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP MANCHESTER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE complex business of defining the features and their metamorphosis into a
finished product is a perennial problem for any manufacturer. In the motor
industry it is compounded by the high costs of developing new models and
ensuring that they meet the demands of the prospective market, writes Philip
Manchester.
Ford's Escort series, for example, has about 300 different 'features'. Every
one of these must be taken from the original marketing vision through to
final production.
Ford of Europe recognised that automating this process was not easy. Its
Product Features Database (PFDB) has a wide audience of users - from the
sales department, through manufacturing and finance to the planning
engineers.
It needed good software tools to help meet this need. 'We were concerned
with user interfaces and, in particular, we wanted to be able to offer
graphical user interfaces to present information to the users. It would not
have been feasible to use a character-based interface,' says Nigel Booth,
manager of pre-production systems with Ford of Europe.
'The system had to be a new and self-contained application - although, at
the same time, it had to be mainframe-based to cope with shared databases,'
Booth adds.
In 1990, when Ford decided to go ahead with the new PFDB application, it
looked around for tools to get the project moving quickly.
'We were not looking for rapid application development tools specifically -
but we needed something which would give us a way to prototype the systems
and show them to the users early on,' explains project manager Peter Harris.
'We looked at a lot of packages to do this. But they were all based on
low-level programming languages and would need custom-built code to do the
job.'
Ford chose Easel, a software development tool specifically aimed at
providing graphical user interface (GUI) based applications for mainframe
environments. The product features a database which sits on an IBM mainframe
server and is accessed by the Easel-built applications. Easel has features
which allow it to capture standard IBM mainframe instructions and present
them in GUI format.
Ford was able to get the whole system up and working in about six months
which, by mainframe standards, is quick. The real bonuses came, however,
from the ability to build prototypes to show users in the design phase and
the ability to make changes at the front end without affecting the mainframe
system.
'I am not sure if the system is either quicker or slicker as a result. But
we feel we got better quality end products. And by putting the presentation
software on the PC we can make changes at a much faster pace,' notes Harris.
</TEXT>
<XX>
