<HEADLINE>
FT  08 SEP 93 / Survey of Software at Work - Autumn 1993 (17): Complex
contract was worth Pounds 15m - Large-Scale Application: East Anglian health
authority - Continuing reforms within the health service will bring a
shake-up in health IT, and fresh opportunities for private sector operators
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN KAVANAGH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
EAST ANGLIA, like other regions, ran a central mainframe computer service
for its eight districts. But in 1989 the government announced its Working
for Patients initiative, which handed much more autonomy not only to
districts but also individual hospitals, which could become largely
independent trusts.
'We consulted the staff very closely and there was general agreement that
they were having trouble providing a viable service,' says Keith Heron,
general manager at Huntingdon district and also chairman of the regional
computing committee.
'NHS salaries are not great and people were at the top of the scales. Our
location in Cambridge meant we were training people who were then filched by
local companies and the Science Park. We were not able to retain the best
people and had trouble recruiting good staff, so we had quite a few
vacancies.
'The staff and the users were gradually all coming to the view that we had
to look at the private sector.'
Staff were also consulted during the evaluation of suppliers. The short-list
was three of the top six suppliers: Hoskyns, Sema and Data Sciences. These
companies spoke to the regional committee at meetings which also included
staff representatives. There were then meetings between the companies and
the staff representatives alone. 'Both staff and management felt most
confident about Sema's attitude towards employing our staff, transferring
their terms and conditions, training and career development,' Heron says.
'There was a guarantee of no redundancies for three years: that was one
reason for going to Sema and some of our staff have done exceptionally well
there, gaining promotion and better training and career paths by working for
a big computing company. This also meant we would continue to be supported
by people who had NHS knowledge in general and experience of our systems in
particular.
'In addition, although we would have contractual commitment from the
directors, just as important was their personal attitude. Sema was not the
cheapest, although close to it, so our selection was clearly not based
solely on cost.'
Sema was awarded a complex contract which nominally ran for five years and
was worth Pounds 15m. The company took on 100 region computing staff: most
have moved to a Cambridge site now set up by Sema. It also took over an ICL
mainframe computer and two big DEC Vax minicomputer configurations.
Applications on these and local machines range from payroll to patient
administration.
'In a sense we have not saved any money,' Heron says. 'The proposal was that
the supplier would take over everything - in effect the existing budget -
and we would also pay a management fee. However, we had some unfilled
vacancies, so that was reflected in the budget.
'Sema took over our equipment, which is leased, but charge it back to us at
19 per cent. With interest rates much lower now, we are looking at buying
out the lease.
'The main benefit was that we got a viable service, both for maintaining the
existing systems and for future development.'
The contract guaranteed Sema Pounds 9m for running the existing service over
the first three years of the new health service structure.
During that time the districts and the 30 hospitals and other trusts would
work on their future computing needs and could install their own systems.
After three years they could break with the central service, taking their
service funds with them.
The remaining Pounds 6m was not guaranteed, although it includes a system
development element arranged in a way which encourages districts financially
to go to Sema.
As Heron puts it: 'Sema took quite a risk on operational services but less
risk on development services.'
Even so, he points out that the health service reforms mean that instead of
dealing with just eight districts, Sema also now has to negotiate with the
30 trusts.
Sema's marketing director, Paul Hopkins, says some trusts are moving some
systems from the old mainframe to program packages running on smaller local
machines. But he thinks Sema is in a strong position to retain much of the
business beyond the end of the contract.
'We're now working on convincing trusts that they should concentrate on
delivering health care and leave us to concentrate on delivering information
technology,' he says.
SUPPLIER PROFILE
Sema Group PLC was created in 1988 from the merger of the long-established
UK computing services company, CAP, and French company Sema-Metra. The group
has 3,500 staff, including 1,000 in the facilities management division.
It has been in facilities management for 20 years
Offices: Sema has three IBM and four ICL computer centres, including those
in Glasgow, Birmingham and across central and southern England.
Turnover and profit: 1991 turnover Pounds 412.5m (including Pounds 43m from
a subsidiary which was sold); pre-tax profit Pounds 14.2m. 1992 Pounds
416.7m; pre-tax profit Pounds 19.5m. Facilities management is 14 per cent of
turnover. Market research says the company is third or fourth in the UK
facilities management business.
Price: Contracts typically last three or five years. Annual contract costs
range from Pounds 500,000 to Pounds 10m.
Clients: 40-50.
</TEXT>
