<PROFILE>_AN-DIHB8AHJFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>930908
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  08 SEP 93 / Survey of Software at Work - Autumn 1993 (14): The early
bird gets the worm - Consultant's Critique
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
AN astronaut was once asked what was the scariest part of going into space.
He answered that, looking around at all the high-technology equipment needed
to keep him alive, it was the knowledge that the work went to the lowest
tender.
Westminster City Council wisely looked at issues other than price in
choosing a company for facilities management (FM). Recognising that the IT
system had the potential to totally disrupt operations, Mr Roots looked at
other issues - particularly how the council felt that the company and they
would work together.
Facilities management is often described as 'out-sourcing your redundancy
plan'. Westminster saw that as more and more councils looked at FM, there
would be a glut of former IT staff. The first to act would secure the best
deals in placing their people.
FM is an example of obtaining advantage through efficient asset management.
ITNet is doing nothing secret or proprietary. It is doing nothing that
Westminster could not have done for itself except to provide management in
specialist areas. Westminster council has decided that its core business is
managing the city infrastructure and welfare. IT is not seen to be part of
that core.
ITNet also concentrates on maximising its human assets. It spent a lot of
time selecting the people they wanted to transfer from Westminster City
Council. ITNet used independent assessment centres and psychometric tests
for senior personnel. Since the handover, it has used MORI to poll staff for
their views.
It seems that both sides benefit from the deal. Westminster is able to get
its IT services at a competitive price and avoids most of the redundancy
costs. ITNet gets a London base, some equipment and an excellent reference
site for future contracts. Whether other councils will get such a good deal
is open to debate.
Lessons from this case:
There is more to long-term contracts than the price.
Stick to areas of management competence.
The early bird gets the worm.
KEVIN GRUMBALL The author is a consultant with Software Design and
Construction, of Milton Keynes
</TEXT>
<XX>
Companies:-
</XX>
<CO>ITNet.
</CO>
