<HEADLINE>
FT  08 SEP 93 / Survey of Software at Work - Autumn 1993 (11): Let the
experts take over - Viewpoint / Contracting out is one way of passing the IT
buck to people who promise to tame it.  John Kavanagh assesses the risks and
benefits
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN KAVANAGH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
NO company would seriously consider devoting management and other resources
to setting up and running its own electricity supply business just to meet
its own needs - yet this is just what organisations in effect do with
information technology (IT).
That is one argument used by the increasing number of computing facilities
management companies entering a market worth over Dollars 2,500m in Europe
and growing by more than 20 per cent a year. Indeed, market research firm
Dataquest predicts that UK spending on facilities management will overtake
sales of mainframe computers within five years.
Facilities management typically involves contracting out the running of
computers and systems. Equipment and staff generally transfer to the
supplier, although they might continue working at the customer's premises
for a while. Sometimes the contract is signed with a long-term relationship
in mind; but an increasing proportion of contracts involve the supplier
running the existing service for three to five years while the customer
moves to new technology and systems: for example from a central mainframe to
a network of local minicomputers or personal computers.
Even organisations with the very biggest computing units are looking at
facilities management: the latest notable example is the Inland Revenue,
which is examining tenders for its entire set-up of three development
centres, a dozen computer centres and more than 2,300 staff.
Cutting costs is not the main reason organisations go for facilities
management, according to a 1993 survey by services company CMG. Its findings
are confirmed by interviews carried out for this survey.
The CMG survey shows the main reasons for choosing facilities management are
a lack of internal skills or resources, mentioned by 36 per cent of users,
the need to focus on core business activities (27 per cent), cost reductions
(23 per cent) and flexibility in the use and expansion of computing (eight
per cent).
The survey also shows that these benefits actually happen. More than 75 per
cent of users said facilities management had freed management to concentrate
on core business. In addition, 70 per cent said facilities management had
reduced staff numbers.
Other benefits realised include greater financial control of operations (48
per cent), reduced running costs (47 per cent), the elimination of staff
management problems (45 per cent), improved or guaranteed service levels (43
per cent) and the removal of staff shortages and recruitment problems (43
per cent).
There were mixed results on overall cost savings: 56 per cent reported
savings, 29 per cent said there was no change and 15 per cent said costs had
increased. Indeed, when asked about the disadvantages of facilities
management, 40 per cent of current users said there were no real cost
reductions - this was the biggest single group.
Even so, there were bigger votes for the benefits than for the
disadvantages. Other disadvantages mentioned were difficulties in defining
boundaries of responsibility (35 per cent), loss of in-house expertise (27
per cent), poor understanding by the supplier of the client's business (17
per cent), poor accountability (16 per cent) and loss of control of IT
services and strategy (14 per cent).
Many of these disadvantages are related and highlight the need, now being
underlined by service suppliers, to regard facilities management as a
partnership. All those arguments about IT being key to business strategy and
competitive advantage mean contracting out this area is not as
straightforward as signing away the canteen arrangements or office cleaning.
'Facilities management is gradually moving from being seen as an IT function
to being regarded as a business management service,' says Mr John Rioch,
head of CMG's facilities management services. 'This means users are
demanding more from their supplier relationship. They require a degree of
partnership, but current arrangements often fail to deliver in this
respect.'
This view is backed by other suppliers and confirmed by the CMG survey: less
than a quarter of users said facilities management was totally integrated
with theirbusiness strategy, although 48 per cent said there was partial
integration.
Without a strategic partnership, a company's IT is in danger of stagnating,
according to Mr Geoff Symons, a partner in the Nolan, Norton division of
consultancy KPMG, who advises companies considering facilities management.
This is especially true when the contract includes system development. He
says companies need to retain the ability to manage the service and the
relationship from the customer side.
Facilities management, then, must not be an abdication of management (it has
been argued that FM stands for 'failed management'). Indeed, all the users
interviewed for this survey have clear IT strategies in place: Westminster
City Council even delayed going out to tender while it put together such a
strategy.
'You must look at your management practices and your systems first,' says Mr
Bob Aylott, a principal consultant at KPMG. 'If they're unstable it can be
difficult to find a solid reference against which to measure the supplier's
service. And you might be giving a blank cheque to the supplier to get the
systems in order.'
Geoff Symons says such reviews of current practice can make companies think
about how the prospective supplier makes its profit - and whether its
economies can be achieved in-house.
However, Mr Simon Ricketts, managing director of service supplier ITnet,
suggests this is unlikely - 'a big supplier can get better computer leasing
and software licensing deals than individual clients,' he says. 'As
specialists we work faster and more efficiently across all the client
contracts. By far the biggest money maker is our tuning of the equipment to
make better use of the capacity by rationalising the workload across a
smaller number of machines.'
Such an insight into a supplier's business is useful at the negotiation
stage. 'The ability to negotiate is vital,' says Geoff Symons at KPMG.
Several big suppliers argue that some companies are so keen to expand or
break into this fast-growing market that they are taking contracts at an
initial loss, hoping to build up other work in two or three years from the
same client. There are fears that this will hit the industry's reputation.
John Rioch at CMG believes the relationship and accountability problems
highlighted by his company's survey justify these fears.
But there is no escaping the growth of a business which is attracting
customers of the size of the Inland Revenue and BP. Even the big computer
manufacturers, are moving into the market to help protect their future.
'No-one has all the management skills and professional resources to be world
class at everything they do,' says Mr Mark Otway, who runs FM services at
Andersen Consulting. 'Contracting out is a pragmatic response to reality.'
The Computing Services Association is a good first stop for companies
considering facilities management. It has a client briefing note and a code
of practice for suppliers and numbers all the main suppliers among its
members. The association is at Hanover House, 73 High Holborn, London WC1V
6LE; telephone 071-405 2171.
