<HEADLINE>
FT  08 SEP 93 / Survey of Software at Work - Autumn 1993 (10): A resource
for small companies - Virtual Office in Devon
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CLAIRE GOODING
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
JANE YATES, manager of Deer Park Telecentre, is no newcomer to teleworking.
She deals with the membership of the National Association of Teleworkers, a
register of resources for teleworkers who want to find work on the open
market, which uses the Telecentre as its headquarters.
Now she also runs the Deer Park Telecentre, which she describes as 'a
virtual office,' officially opened on April 27 this year.
It grew from an existing service to business people staying at the Deer Park
Hotel at Weston, near Honiton in Devon, and is so far not a member of the
Telecottage Association.
'We see ourselves as a temporary office, a resource for small businesses who
don't want to tie up capital in equipment,' she explains.
But her brief goes further - 'People tend to think that the equipment is the
most important part of the scenario. But what we provide is the skill behind
that to deal with problems, particularly the confidence in using the
equipment.
'We try to get rid of the phobia some people have about the technology by
giving hands-on help, in privacy if people prefer.'
Digital Equipment (DEC) has played a large part in establishing the centre,
particularly in providing training, while the Worshipful Company of
Information Technologists has also been a valuable source of support and
guidance. There is a dedicated host modem linked to Digital's own offices
for the use of visiting employees and other visitors, which gives the Centre
another role - that of demonstration centre for live teleworking.
As well as providing back-up and support for the courses and conferences at
the hotel, (mostly for directors and senior executives), Deer Park provides
a secretarial service which embraces everything from general typing to a
personalised answering service, mail shots and creating transparencies and
acetates for presentations.
There are also two private rooms for hire, described as 'telephone kiosks of
the 21st century.' These provide business users with a private room on a
flexible hire basis, with use of fax, phone, PC, modem and printer.
'There are lots of skills the south-east, but they need to be co-ordinated,'
concludes Jane Yates. 'Quality control has to be carried out to a high
standard.'
</TEXT>
