<HEADLINE>
FT  08 SEP 93 / Survey of Software at Work - Autumn 1993 (6): The fax of
life in rural Oxfordshire - Small Company Application / Stonesfield
Telecottage
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CLAIRE GOODING
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
STONE walls along the road to Stonesfield mark the estate boundary of
Blenheim Palace, but the route cuts straight through miles of uninhabited
countryside before it arrives at a very different set of buildings. This is
Stonesfield, an unpretentious village whose character comes not from
postcard cosiness, but from steep tiled roofs and houses set at odd angles
to one another and to the road which curls around them at impossible angles.
Stonesfield's identity reflects its geological siting - on a rock which
provided the slates for all the Oxford colleges and yielded the first
discovery of a dinosaur bones in the 1880s. In the 1990s, Stonesfield has
its fair share of re-vamped barns and baronial executive homes on the
outskirts, but it remains a working village, not a dormitory, despite
redundancies at Cowley which have devastated the local economy.
Friends Close is in the centre, a new cluster of open, airy houses
reminiscent of a Scandinavian style. Above, on a tree, a small sign
'Stonesfield Telecottage' leads visitors up some garden steps which, like
the road, wind up and and around and finally down, into an airy room where
sits Kathy Coonerty, at an Apple Macintosh, and Tony Crofts, at a desk
loaded with papers.
Kathy, manager of the office, is typesetting magazine copy on the Apple
IICx. As well as being the manager, accountant and hub of the office, she
earns much of the revenue by typing. She has one-off jobs, such as a
recently-completed student thesis; regular clients including a local
novelist, Jenny Hinton; and she does typesetting and pagemaking for a
variety of newsletters.
A new customer leaves with 10p worth of photocopying. Howard Bond walked
from his home to the telecottage to copy a letter from the BBC. 'I read
about this service in the local news sheet, the Slate,' he explains. 'Now I
know it's here I'll use it again.'
The next customer is on the telephone: an inquiry from a Bosnian who wants
to enrol on a correspondence course for Teaching English as a Foreign
Language (TEFL). This is another business based at the telecottage, run by
Jim Wingate, who develops courseware and writes books for Intered in Vienna.
Tony Crofts deals with the inquiry and adds another letter to the pile which
Kathy will take with her to the post office when she leaves for the day. The
office also hosts a drama group and other local afternoon activities.
Although Kathy only works 12 hours a week, on Mondays, Tuesdays, Wednesdays
and Fridays, the door is always open. The telecottage itself is built on the
back of Crofts' higgledy-piggledy house, all gables and steps. Built
originally as a self-contained bachelor flat, with hand-made floor tiles and
a loft-bed reached by a ladder, it was destined to evolve into a study,
office and then telecottage, all part of Croft's campaign to bring
affordable housing, owned and run at community level, to Stonesfield.
Kathy joined Crofts initially as a secretary, having seen an advertisement
in the Slate. She became the manager when the telecottage started in April
1989. She had relocated in Stonesfield for her husband's work, and her
experience made her an ideal candidate for the job. She had evaluated
various word processing packages from their earliest days, when employed at
Thames Polytechnic and the Borough of Lewisham, and had also been involved
in training.
'Once you got over the initial fear, people loved using the system' she
says, recalling that those initially terrifed of computers often became the
most effective users, irrespective of age.
Now she works on the Macintosh and has added magazine layout to her skills,
as well as doing occasional training. She is self-employed and paid by the
hour. The Mac was chosen for ease of use and its power in design jobs such
as typesetting and pagemaking. Its only disadvantage is that most women
'returners' wish to learn skills on DOS-based computers.
Crofts is himself a TEFL trainer and agricultural journalist specialising in
environmental and rural matters. He charges no rent to the telecottage
business, but instead uses its facilities for his own work and deals with
all incoming inquiries outside Kathy's hours.
His wife, Randi Berild, an architect from Norway, has her own studio in a
gabled room in the main part of the house. The couple take it in turns to
work and share the childcare of their three-year-old son.
As well as Jim Wingate, Tony Crofts and Randi Berild, there are nine other
local businesses in the same street. There are three business consultants
(including one who is only resident at weekends), a woman who manufactures
custom-designed jogging suits, a couple who arrange fine-art holiday tours,
a graphic designer and another freelance architect. All use the telecottage
facilities on an occasional basis. Others, still struggling to find more
conventional employment, keep their CVs on the Macintosh and Kathy updates
them for each new job application.
The local colour is a necessary accompaniment to understanding the function
of the Stonesfield telecottage and the important part it plays both for
local businesses and, as the hub of a campaign for housing provided by the
community, for the community. No telecottage is 'typical' but Stonesfield is
less remote than many.
The village, a few miles from Oxford and within easy reach of the extended
M40, has suffered similar problems to many other picturesque places, as
wealthy middle-class incomers knock together small terraces to make spacious
ranches. House prices, even in the slump, have risen well above what local
people can afford, particularly the young couples and single people who
would not even merit one point on the council housing list.
Tony Croft's involvement with local housing has its roots in his job as a
rural journalist. He moved to Stonesfield in 1976 and subsequently worked
for British Farmer and Stockbreeder, an IPC (now Reed) publication based in
Sutton, Surrey. Remarkably, he persuaded IPC to allow him to do 'distance
working' because he had to be rurally-based, and it made economic sense to
visit Sutton only once weekly. He now runs the newsletter for RURAL
(Responsible Uses of Resources in Agriculture and on the Land), the
countryside information policy group.
He was further inspired by the 'father of the telecottage movement', the
late Henning Albrechtsen. On his way to Leningrad in 1988 he visited the
telecottage that Albrechtsen, a former UN interpreter and oil executive, had
set up above a supermarket in a remote corner of north Sweden, Vemdalen.
This centre provides the same quality of work as can be found in central
Stockholm, but to remote business clients, and at comparable rates. There
are now 80 such centres thriving all over Scandinavia.
When the pub next door, the Boot, was closed and sold for a house
conversion, Crofts wanted to see its adjoining land and car park put to
good, community-based use.
'Planning should be done at parish level. I believe in devolution to
community level. Houses should be built on the basis of need, not
profitability.'
The six dwellings in Friends Close are the result (see panel) and the
telecottage is an important contributor to funds.
He sees no point in letting prime land go to developers who build dwellings
inappropriate to local needs, pocket the profit and put nothing back into
the community.
'There's a tremendous potential for local democracy currently not being put
to use by the system,' he says. 'Decisions made in higher tiers of
government, usually urban-based, are often wide of the mark.'
Crofts' idealism is matched by business sense and a long-term view. A second
housing scheme of five houses is taking shape in the centre of the village,
on a prime site which once housed the Rose and Crown pub and the old village
school playground. It has been funded by Mercury Provident, the Ecology
Building Society, county and district council grants, the Central Telethon
Trust, the Marlborough Charitable Trust, and two other charities.
There are also a number of private supporters who have invested their money
as debenture loans, secured on some of the property over 12 years at a fixed
10 per cent interest. This guarantees a steady interest, and enables SCT to
draw realistic cash flows.
This method has been very successful, raising Pounds 60,000 in two months
from an advertisement in the Friend, a Quaker publication.
Crofts is now looking at a third project, funded the same way. This would
provide workspace for small businesses and a new home for the telecottage,
providing central services for everyone. In an ideal world, the post office
would be on the same site and be part of the mutually supportive local
network.
'A little nest of complementary activities,' Crofts calls it. The rural
idyll is no mere dream and, he suggests, is achievable with local support
and understanding: 'West Oxfordshire District Council has been wonderful -
they have backed promising projects. Local supporters have created a climate
where things can happen.'
</TEXT>
