<HEADLINE>
FT  08 SEP 93 / Survey of Software at Work - Autumn 1993 (3): Roses around
the door and a fax on the Welsh dresser - Analysis / 'Teleworking' and the
'telecottage' sound appealing and can be productive.  Claire Gooding
examines the issues facing employers and teleworkers who want to benefit
from this new way of working
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CLAIRE GOODING
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
DISTANCE is no object for productive teleworkers, be they in a
high-technology telecottage, or cosy at home. It's a pleasure to get up in
the morning without having to think about what to wear for the office. To
spend less time waiting for trains or grinding gears and teeth in a traffic
jam makes sense on a personal level but also has wider environmental
benefits.
It is nearly 20 years since computer companies started talking about the
benefits of teleworking. IT companies were particularly well-suited to
exploiting the technology of the time. The FI Group, founded as F
International, built up its network of programmers initially from women
programmers working from home.
As the technology developed, computer companies such as Digital Equipment
and IBM invested in offices adapted to 'hot desking', a term used to
describe the sharing of one desk space by two or more people who work
largely from home and go into the office occasionally.
Terrorist attacks on city centres provide another powerful incentive for
'outworking.' Digital was up and working within days after its headquarters
was gutted by fire in 1990 - a rapid recovery which it attributes to its
flexible working patterns, including teleworking.
In the past 10 years PCs have become more affordable and the software
running on them easier to use. Where a local support team was once a
necessity, people can now work with 'sitalone' software: software so
self-explanatory that it needs no support or explanation such as on a
Macintosh or under PC Windows.
On the telecommunications front, there is ISDN - Integrated Services Digital
Network - which can support such applications as videophones, split signals
(serving fax, voice, modem and so on, on one line) and high-speed data
transmission. ISDN telephone lines are beginning to come into service and in
parts of Scotland are already part of the telework culture. Companies such
as Jaguar Communications of St Albans specialise in providing modems and
plug-in ISDN cards for connecting PCs.
Telemessaging and electronic mail (e-mail) systems such as British Telecom's
Mailbox and the Compulink's Cix remove the constraints of time-barriers.
Workers using such mail systems can choose their own working times.
Chris Moller of the Home Office Partnership points out that there are
several ways of working at home with PCs, modems and fax.
'There are three categories: in the first are employees with formal support
for working at home; self-motivated, educated people for whom the job itself
is the reward. In the second category are people involved with repetitive,
humdrum tasks, such as telesales. Teleworking is less practical for them,
partly because it is only the social contact that makes the job bearable.
'The third category is of specialists, largely freelance, doing such jobs as
translating. In effect they are free-standing: the work finds them.'
Working at home demands the skillswith which any freelance is familiar, and
computer skills come low on the list. The first is self-discipline and the
second comes under 'marketing.'
The National Teleworking Advisory Council (NTAC) is a forum set up to help
individuals and organisations exploring teleworking, founded by the
Worshipful Company of Information Technologists.
'We're evolving a code of practice, a guide for employees and employers
alike,' says chairman Peter Monson.
Most non-technical teleworkers, he points out, need help with the basics of
equipping themselves, such as printer interfaces, maintenance agreements,
telemessage systems, even voltage supply.
Sue Blacker, of the Devon and Cornwall Development Co in Lostwithiel,
Cornwall, is another NTAC member with a City of London background whose
concerns range from the technical (such as scanners versus modems), to the
management issues of contracts, pay, and promotion. She agrees that
marketing is a difficulty.
'If you give your address as Rose Cottage, it sounds as though you're not up
to the job. Why should an employer take the risk if there's a building full
of people on the spot who can do it? There are a lot of psychological
problems to overcome.'
Qualifications are one way for the isolated teleworker to convince agency or
employer that work carried out at arm's length can be relied on. Although
work on National Vocational Qualifications is under way, it does not remove
all the problems, one of which, according to Barney Gibbens, head of the
Information Technology Training Organisation (ITITO), is the difficulty of
assessing remote trainees.
'We hope there will be assessment centres all over the country, not just set
up by colleges, but by large employers, so trainees can visit local
centres,' he says.
Organisation and Technology Research's much-quoted report in 1991 took the
view that teleworking offered benefits to employees, but not necessarily
financial.
The telecottage movement stresses that it is promoting rural work at urban
rates - not second-class workers, paid at a lower rate.
There is evidence of a significant change of attitude in recent years.
Selling is one well-paid activity that seems to work well at long distance.
Unipart is not alone in devolving its sales to home-based workers. Sun
Alliance's Adam project, involving 27 home workers, and Marion Merrell Dow,
with 88 home-based sales and regional managers, both use the Oxygen system
for remote selling.
Many companies interviewed for this survey reported a sympathetic, rather
than a sceptical attitude to their home base. 'Not so long ago,' said one,
'people on the phone would think worse of you if they could hear the dog
barking or the children yelling in the background. Now they say, lucky you,
to be able to work at home.'
Francis Kinsman, futurist and writer of The Telecommuters, is a great source
of entertaining statistics on teleworking, which he sees as part of a wider
movement towards flexible work patterns. In his address to the recent
European Conference on Distance Working, he quoted the Henley Centre for
Forecasting's estimate that 15 per cent of work in the UK will be performed
remotely by 1995.
In Kinsman's opinion, the UK is well-placed to take advantage of this
radical change in work patterns. 'The Highlands and Islands and the Grampian
regions, because of ISDN, are aggressively looking to steal Pounds 100,000
worth of financially-based jobs from the south-east over the next decade.'
The real emphasis, he said, should be on flexible working and the networked
organisation, a model being explored by Tesco, Berkshire County Council,
Mercury, and Digital Equipment.
According to Kinsman, the 21st century might well become the era of the
telescab, with sophisticated information skills coming cheaply from an
international marketplace that includes the Philippines, Malaysia, and
China.
'The danger is that if we can do it, others can. London Underground tried
nine different UK software houses for its new timing system and settled for
a developer in Bombay at 40 per cent of the cost. There's a lesson there.'
</TEXT>
