<HEADLINE>
FT  08 SEP 93 / London Stock Exchange: Equity futures and options trading
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOEL KIBAZO
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
FEARS THAT the Bundesbank may not, after all, reduce German interest rates
this week led to strong selling in Footsie futures in London yesterday,
sending the underlying cash market lower, writes Joel Kibazo.
The high of the day for the September contract on the FT-SE 100, recorded at
3,070, came within minutes. Thereafter, the future came under selling
pressure as the doubts over a reduction in German rates took hold. That
sentiment soon spread from derivatives to the equity market, bringing a
sell-off there also.
The September future fell to a discount to cash of 5 points just after
midday, a move that was repeated several times over the next few hours,
although it traded in line with cash for most of the session.
The day's low of 3,035 was registered in the last half-hour of business, but
nerves steadied before the close and September finished at 3,042, a 4-point
premium to the cash market. Volume in the near month contract was a healthy
11,084 lots, while that in the December contract, which closed at 3,064, was
3,040 lots.
Turnover in traded options improved to 30,728 contracts from Monday's poor
level of 20,044. However, business in the FT-SE 100 option was below
Monday's total, reaching 7,866 lots by the close. A big buyer of the
December 40 calls in Amstrad sent its volume to 6,640 contracts.
</TEXT>
