<HEADLINE>
FT  08 SEP 93 / UK Company News: Brown &amp; Jackson loss rises to Pounds 11.4m
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID BLACKWELL
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BROWN &amp; JACKSON, owner of the Poundstretcher discount retail chain, fell
deeper into the red in the first half of 1993.
The pre-tax loss increased from Pounds 9.73m to Pounds 11.45m. However, Mr
Ian Gray, chief executive, said yesterday that the group historically had
made a loss in the first half as Poundstretcher is highly dependent on
Christmas trading, with 50 per cent of turnover coming between September and
December.
Turnover rose by 4.7 per cent from Pounds 63.8m to Pounds 66.8m. The group
said like-for-like sales in Poundstretcher were 5.5 per cent ahead. Toiletry
sales rose 30 per cent and confectionery sales 20 per cent.
B&amp;J, which operates 230 stores, is now one year into its three-year recovery
plan. Three months ago it had a Pounds 21m rights issue, its second in just
over a year, to reduce borrowings and finance a store opening programme.
Interest payments fell in the half to Pounds 851,000 against Pounds 2.12m
and the company had net cash of Pounds 2.1m at June 30.
Losses per share fell from 5.4p to 2.5p.
Mr Gray said yesterday that significant progress had been made with the
group's recovery plan. He blamed the increased loss on margin reductions
from the clearance of slow-moving stock early in the year, and more than
Pounds 2m of capital expenditure, including the installation of an
electronic point of sale system.
Working capital had been cut, mainly through a 10 per cent reduction in
stocks. This had been achieved without the benefits of Epos and at a time of
rising sales.
There is no interim dividend.
</TEXT>
