<HEADLINE>
FT  08 SEP 93 / UK Company News: Scholl dips to Pounds 11.7m mid-way
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CATHERINE MILTON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
HIGH marketing and develop-ment investment cost Scholl, the healthcare
company, a dip in pre-tax profits to Pounds 11.7m in the six months to June
30, compared with last time's Pounds 13.7m, which was flattered by Pounds
2.4m in higher investment and one-off gains.
Mr Neil Franchino, chief executive, said the company had so far outperformed
rivals as recession swept continental Europe: 'There is a problem and we
can't stay above it for ever. We can't be any more optimistic than other
people. I am terribly concerned about continental Europe even if we fared
fairly well.'
Turnover rose to Pounds 94.1m (Pounds 85.8m), with about 5 per cent of the
gain attributable to currency movements and the rest to improvements in
third party distribution sales, including a contract with Bristol Myers in
Germany, and about 26 per cent growth in the Asia region, and 6 per cent in
Australia.
The company made two acquisitions in the first half of 1992. The Scholl
retail chain in Canada opened four additional stores bringing the total to
24, with three more planned by the year end. The Gerard House herbal
remedies company increased distribution from about 1,800 to nearly 5,000
points of sale.
It bought Septivon, the antiseptic wash brand, in June from Elf Sanofi for
FF125m (Pounds 14.7m) cash, plus taxes of FF8.5m (Pounds 1m).
Scholl said results had been brought down at the half year by a change in
the business mix: 'We used to be in a situation where all profit was made in
the first half. Last year the split was roughly 75 per cent in the first
half and the remaining quarter in the second and this trend is likely to
continue this year.'
At halfway the company had Pounds 6m (Pounds 19.4m) in cash and borrowings
of Pounds 5.7m (Pounds 2.8m).
The board declared a maintained interim dividend of 2.6p out of earnings of
9.3p (11.2p).
</TEXT>
