<HEADLINE>
FT  08 SEP 93 / Nippon Steel in Pounds 98m loss
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By EMIKOO TERAZONO
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   TOKYO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
NIPPON Steel, the world's largest steel company, yesterday announced that it
would post at least Y15bn (Pounds 98m) in pre-tax losses for the year
because of the prolonged economic slump and the sharp appreciation of the
yen, writes Emiko Terazono in Tokyo. The company had earlier hoped for a
pre-tax profit of Y20bn.
Other steelmakers - Kobe, Kawasaki, NKK and Sumitomo Metal Industries - are
scheduled to revise forecasts on Friday.
Mr Shigeru Omori, Nippon Steel's vice-president, admitted the losses would
be greater, but for realisation of profits from its securities portfolio. It
will skip its interim dividend. Sales for the first half are expected to
fall 8 per cent to Y1,090bn. The company revised its forecast for first-half
year losses down from Y5bn to Y15bn. For the second half, Mr Omori said:
'The best our company can hope for is to post no profits but no losses
either.' In 1992-93 pre-tax profits plunged by 71.2 per cent to Y28.9bn.
</TEXT>
