<HEADLINE>
FT  08 SEP 93 / Deal gives S African blacks government role: Multiracial
council will oversee transition
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PATTI WALDMEIR
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   JOHANNESBURG
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
SOUTH AFRICA's constitutional negotiators last night reached a milestone
deal to bring blacks into central government for the first time, by agreeing
to establish a multiparty Transitional Executive Council to oversee the
transfer to democracy.
The authority of the council will be limited, not least by the fact that the
ruling National party is likely to be able to block the council's decisions
in the most important areas. But the council marks the end of 45 years of
exclusive National party rule, and represents a big psychological victory
for black liberation movements - especially the African National Congress,
which has fought apartheid for decades.
The council, which will include one member from each of about 20 parties
negotiating a new constitution, marks the first step towards full
multiracial government. It is the first sign of concrete progress from
constitutional talks that have dragged on for months.
It may ease frustrations in South Africa's black townships, where patience
with the process is wearing thin, and will lead to the lifting of remaining
international economic sanctions apart from oil and arms embargoes.
Mr Thabo Mbeki, ANC chairman, said last night that the decision represented
'another step' towards lifting sanctions, adding that he expected the ANC to
call for their removal later this month. The TEC will take office only when
agreement has been reached on a new constitution - which might still take
weeks or months.
Equally, its installation might provoke a further surge in violence, with
the ultra-right Conservative party and the Inkatha Freedom party of Chief
Mangosuthu Buthelezi vowing to oppose it. The Conservative party said at the
weekend that it would regard the installation of the TEC as a declaration of
civil war, and Inkatha has said it will not respect the TEC's authority in
the KwaZulu black homeland, which it controls.
Other homeland governments have also rejected the council, although most -
including Chief Buthelezi - are leaving open the option of joining the
council later if the new constitution meets their demands.
The TEC will have legally binding powers to act, but only in areas directly
affecting the forthcoming multiracial elections, planned for April 27 next
year.
Its authority will be further circumscribed by the fact that the South
Arican government (one of the parties to the council) will have what amounts
to a veto over its decisions, which must be taken by majorities ranging from
65 per cent to 80 per cent.
Government officials believe Pretoria and its allies could muster the votes
necessary to block TEC decisions.
Pretoria veto, Page 4
</TEXT>
