<HEADLINE>
FT  08 SEP 93 / Gas leak at Thorp N-fuel plant
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BRONWEN MADDOX and CHRIS TIGHE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
STAFF were evacuated from Thorp, the controversial nuclear reprocessing
plant in Cumbria, after a gas leak during tests yesterday.
British Nuclear Fuels, the plant's owner, said last night that 'the work
being carried out was non-radioactive'. It added that there was only a
'slight' escape of gas outside the plant, which posed no danger to the
public.
The leak, which is highly embarrassing for BNF, comes at a sensitive time in
the long-running debate about whether the Pounds 2.8bn plant should get a
licence to start operation.
The current public consultation on the plant's future, the second in the
past year, is due to decide in the autumn whether to give the go-ahead to
the plant, which reprocesses used nuclear fuel.
BNF said last night the incident was embarrassing 'in a way' but added: 'The
tests are being carried out to make sure things do work properly.' The leak
of nitrogen dioxide, which can cause breathing difficulties, occurred at
3.30pm, and BNF sent 280 staff 'in the immediate vicinity' outside the
building. Twenty-five workers were taken to the medical surgery at the West
Cumbrian site for examination before being allowed home. Some are to have a
further medical check today.
Last week BNF won court permission to begin radioactive tests of the
500-metre-long plant, which has taken nearly 10 years to build. But next
week it faces another court challenge from Greenpeace, the pressure group,
which will attempt to halt the tests on the ground that they prejudice the
government's eventual decision.
BNF said last night that the leaking gases were not part of the uranium
testing. Greenpeace said: 'Thorp is meant to be the ultimate in technology
and if BNF can't keep the non-radioactive materials under control, it does
not bode well for the safety of the whole plant.'
It added: 'This has been a bad year for them with leaks.' Earlier in the
year, radioactive gases escaped from two other, unconnected parts of the
Sellafield site.
Yesterday's leak occurred while the gas was being used to test the
ventilation in part of the plant.
</TEXT>
