<HEADLINE>
FT  08 SEP 93 / Upward-only rent reviews defended
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By VANESSA HOULDER, Property Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
RESEARCH contradicting claims that the commercial property market's system
of upward-only rent reviews is inflationary was published yesterday by the
British Property Federation.
'The report shows that, far from being inflationary, upward-only rent
reviews have exerted a strong deflationary influence on the market,' said
the federation which represents landlords.
This came as part of the group's response to a government consultation paper
about possible reforms to the commercial property lease structure. The
system of upward-only rent reviews has been criticised during the recession
because it has prevented rents paid by existing tenants from falling in line
with rents being asked for empty properties.
Although rental values moved faster than retail prices in the early 1970s
and late 1980s, the rate of price inflation exceeded that of rental values
for most of the last 22 years. 'The commercial lease has protected tenants
against the full effects of rental value inflation,' the report says.
Tenants would have paid more if they had replaced the conventional lease
with an agreement to link rent increases to retail price inflation in each
of the last 22 years except for 1989 and 1990.
If the structure were changed, rents would rise in the longer term to
protect investors against increased uncertainty and risk, the report says.
Critics of the system include the Bank of England, which said earlier this
year that 'upwards-only rent review clauses seem designed for a world which
had the certainty of an upwards-only pattern of property values'.
The options in the consultation paper include prohibiting upward-only
reviews and allowing rents to move either up or down, but never below the
initial rent.
</TEXT>
