<HEADLINE>
FT  08 SEP 93 / Victims of cancer treatment to sue
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD LAPPER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
AT LEAST six cancer patients wrongly diagnosed at Birmingham's Royal
Orthopaedic hospital are to sue for compensation, triggering a potential
flood of litigation against the local area health authority at the centre of
the case.
Five solicitors have already received instructions from clients and a
further two expect to do so in the next few days, according to the Law
Society, which has set up a service to co-ordinate actions.
'People have come to expect high standards,' said Mr Stephen Jones, a
partner with Pannone &amp; Partners, who added that the amount of litigation has
risen in the past seven to eight years. Pannone is representing Ms Vicki
Hunter, a 20-year-old PE student who lost part of her right leg as a result
of unnecessary cancer treatment.
Diagnostic errors have so far been identified in 42 cases handled by Dr
Carol Starkie for the hospital's bone-tumour unit. About 1,600 more cases
will be re-examined over the next three to four months, and the total of
misdiagnosed patients is expected to reach 100.
Solicitors for plaintiffs point out that recent changes in legal-aid rules
will make it more difficult for families to obtain help to finance actions.
'Changes may mean that people won't take action,' said Mr Tony Hall, of
Birmingham-based Anthony Collins, who is representing Matthew Guest, a
nine-year-old who received unnecessary chemotherapy treatment.
Even so, the cost to South Birmingham Health Authority could run into
millions of pounds, highlighting the burden of medical negligence claims for
both hospitals and general practitioners.
The Medical Defence Union, one of three mutual insurance schemes which
provides cover for GPs, said claims reached Pounds 28.5m last year, with
costs increasing by at least 15 per cent annually in recent years.
Health authorities are not insured for medical negligence claims and must
meet most of the costs of awards from their own budgets. Ms Cheryl Blundell,
a medical negligence specialist with Berrymans, the firm of solicitors which
acts for defendants, suggested that authorities could be stretched by the
cost of awards, which can reach more than Pounds 1m. The Law Society is
considering further legal action against the Lord Chancellor over his latest
plans to cut legal-aid pay.
From November Lord Mackay is proposing to pay solicitors a fixed hourly rate
set by him for civil legal-aid work. At present fees are set by district
judges.
The society claims Lord Mackay's proposed hourly rate of Pounds 65 is about
25 per cent less than the average now allowed by district judges.
</TEXT>
