<HEADLINE>
FT  08 SEP 93 / Growers attack forestry sell-off
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JAMES BUXTON, Scottish Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE GOVERNMENT has been urged not to privatise the Forestry Commission's
woodlands by the Forestry Industry Committee of Great Britain, whose members
are mainly private-sector timber growers and processors.
The committee says it is the wrong time to privatise Forest Enterprise, the
Forestry Commission division which owns and manages 2m acres of woodland.
The committee says market conditions for a sale are poor, Forest Enterprise
has only recently been created and privatisation would divert investment
from planting.
An inter-ministerial committee is reviewing the system of incentives for
tree planting and the ownership of the Forestry Commission's woodlands, with
privatisation an option.
Environmental organisations and the Ramblers Association are against
privatisation, and opposition has also come from Timber Growers UK, whose
members are private forestry owners. and who might be expected to buy some
of the woodlands if they came on the market.
The committee adds that Forest Enterprise should be separated from the
Forestry Commission and be given agency status, which would allow it to
adopt a 'conventional commercial approach, free of the distortions followed
by a government department.'
</TEXT>
