<HEADLINE>
FT  08 SEP 93 / Quango sets course for teacher training reform
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN WILLMAN, Public Policy Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A QUANGO is to be created to supervise the training of schoolteachers in
England, Mr John Patten, education secretary, announced yesterday.
The Teacher Training Agency will distribute funds to universities, colleges
and schools that provide approved initial teacher training.
The agency will shift the emphasis in teacher training to school-based
training and away from college-based courses which many government advisers
hold responsible for falling educational standards.
At present, universities and colleges receive their funds for teacher
training from the Higher Education Funding Council while schools are
directly funded by the Department for Education.
Mr Patten said that establishing a single funding body would 'ensure that
there is a co-ordinated approach to the provision of places and an
appropriate balance between the different types of training'.
The agency will take over the duties of the Teaching as a Career Unit, a
quango that provides information about careers in teaching. The unit will be
wound up and the agency will become a 'one-stop shop' for information and
advice on teaching.
Mr Patten also announced abolition of the Council for the Accreditation of
Teacher Education, the quango responsible for approving teacher-training
courses. Approval of initial teaching qualifications will be given by the
department of education to 'reduce unnecessary bureaucracy and clarify lines
of responsibility'.
</TEXT>
