<HEADLINE>
FT  08 SEP 93 / Smaller companies in leasing firing line
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHARLES BATCHELOR
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A PROPOSAL to extend consumer credit protection legislation to small
companies could lead to a sharp decline in the amount of hire purchase and
leasing finance available to small businesses, the Finance &amp; Leasing
Association warned yesterday, Charles Batchelor writes.
If at the same time the limit of financing agreements covered by the
Consumer Credit Act were to be doubled to Pounds 30,000, an estimated Pounds
830m could be lost to small businesses, the association said.
The warning comes as the Office of Fair Trading is due to publish a
consultation paper on whether the act should be extended to incorporated
businesses. At present it applies only to individuals and unincorporated
businesses.
The Department of Trade and Industry is also considering plans to double the
size of financings covered by the act.
</TEXT>
