<HEADLINE>
FT  08 SEP 93 / Sleepy pineapples arrive fresher
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DELLA BRADSHAW
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
CANADIAN researchers have devised a way of putting pineapples 'to sleep'.
This will prevent the tropical fruit from rotting in transit and means it
will be just ripe enough when it reaches supermarkets in Europe.
First consumers to taste the drowsy but more succulent produce will be in
Scotland, where fruit company Geest is carrying out market trials under the
Necta brand name.
Pineapples have previously been picked before they were ripe to enable them
to withstand damage during shipping. Unlike bananas, which continue to ripen
after picking, pineapples simply begin to rot once they are off the bush.
The Costa Rican pineapples are peeled and cored in a pilot plant before
being packed.
Geest is using modified atmospheric packaging, developed at the University
of British Columbia. This stops rotting by extracting oxygen from the sealed
rigid packing.
'The atmosphere keeps the 'living' fruit fresh, like a cut flower in water,'
explained Mr John Dutton, managing director of Geest's Prepared Produce
division.
When sales trial are launched in Scotland a 500 gram whole cored pineapple
will cost Pounds 1.99, 250 grams of pineapple chunks 99p. It will be next
summer before shoppers in other regions of Britain can taste the fruit.
Mr Dutton, whose company specialises in pre-packed fresh produce, said Necta
would eliminate the messy preparations needed to serve whole fresh
pineapples. 'They (Necta) taste better than most fresh pineapples and the
taste is much more consistent.'
</TEXT>
