<HEADLINE>
FT  08 SEP 93 / Civil Service pension funds trail Abbey on performance
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NORMA COHEN, Investments Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BRITISH Civil Service pensions offer only average benefits when compared
with similar plans offered by private-sector employers, a study has shown.
The study, conducted by Union Pension Services and sponsored by the GMB
general union, found that some banks and financial institutions offer the
best benefits available. The study ranked 100 leading pension schemes in
Britain by the benefits they offered and the contributions required from
employees.
It is the first effort to conduct a systemat comparison of private
employers' benefits. Among factors taken into account were the size of
contributions required from members, statutory increases to benefits, the
rate at which members accrue pension rights, and ancillary benefits such as
ill-health pensions and discretionary benefits.
The top 10 schemes for benefits and contributions were: Abbey National
Scheme, ICI Fund, TSB Group Scheme, Legal and General Fund, Burmah Castrol
Plan, BBC Scheme, Rothmans Fund, Shell Pension Fund, Woolwich Building
Society Fund and Siemans Scheme. The bottom 10 were: Rank Organisation Plan,
DRG Pension Fund (Lower Scale), TI Group Scheme (General Section), Massey
Ferguson Works, Massey Ferguson Staff, Daily Mail Scheme, Harmsworth Scheme,
Philips Pension Fund, NEI (Scale 1) and DRG Pension Fund.
Among civil service schemes, which have historically been reputed to offer
benefits superior to private-sector schemes, the Universities Scheme
achieved the top overall rating of 51 per cent. This compares with the
top-rated private-employer scheme, Abbey National, at 104 per cent.
Pension Scheme Profiles 1993, Union Pension Services Ltd, 50 Trinity
Gardens, London SW9 8DR, Pounds 195 (Pounds 95 for Trade Unions)
</TEXT>
