<HEADLINE>
FT  08 SEP 93 / Ex-Soviet republics bow to Moscow over rouble
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LEYLA BOULTON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MOSCOW
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
FIVE former Soviet republics yesterday pledged to give up their fiscal and
monetary policies as the price for using the Russian rouble as their
currency.
The agreement - signed by Russia, Uzbekistan, Kazakhstan, Tajikistan,
Armenia and Belarus, which decided to join despite already having its own
currency - marks a retreat, in the face of harsh economic reality, from the
republics' declarations of national sovereignty. The accord has still to be
endorsed by national parliaments.
The republics, pushed to make a decision after Russia invalidated pre-1993
rouble notes in circulation on their territory, are fearful of introducing
their own fully-fledged currencies or at least wish to continue receiving
gifts of cash until they are ready to go it alone.
Mr Boris Fyodorov, the Russian finance minister, said the deal allowed the
retention of a common trading area for producers who could not compete on
western markets. He added a transitional period would show which republics
were genuinely keen to build an economic union and which were simply there
for short-term benefits.
The accord sets a transitional period of several months during which it will
be up to the five republics to adjust their economic legislation to Russia's
and conclude bilateral agreements with Moscow, abiding by its monetary and
fiscal targets. In the meantime republics will use their own surrogate
currencies or receive new rouble banknotes with special markings preventing
them being used inside Russia.
Although the rouble zone agreement is designed to prevent republics from
exporting inflation to Russia, political considerations are likely to impede
Moscow's ability to enforce its rules. Uzbekistan, for instance, has already
received a gift of Rbs50bn of new Russian rouble banknotes in a decision
which Mr Alexander Shokhin, deputy prime minister for foreign economic
relations, yesterday described as illegal. Mr Boris Fyodorov, deputy prime
minister and finance minister, said yesterday Russia was not relying on any
new foreign finance before the end of the year. His announcement follows
indications that the IMF will not be disbursing new credits Russia had hoped
to receive this autumn.
</TEXT>
